A few hours after the distention of mindgut a phase of organelle synthesis occurs when additional ribosomes and endoplasmic reticulum are synthesized and organized.
After the organelle synthesis it follows a phase of production of digestive enzymes and absorption of the products of digestion.

The males of a number of diptera taxa aggregate in aerials swarms over conspicuous objects or 'swarm markers'. Conspecific females individually fly to these swarms, but little is known of the responses that take them there. At the assembly stations where male and female insects meet, the females usually are recognized by vision, and among insects that form aerial swarms the eyes of the male are specially developed.

definition.value:
Among some families of Culicimorpha, including the Culicidae, the eyes of males are not especially developed but certain auditory organs are, and the detection of females depends upon hearing. In these flies, the verticillate antennae and highly developed Johnston's organs mediate a sensitivity to the flight tone of conspecific females.
Station-keeping swarms are formed by the members of certain families of Diptera, Ephemeroptera and Trichoptera, and to a lesser extend by representatives of the Hymenoptera and a few other insect orders. The assembly station is attended by both sexes, but usually the males fly there for long periods whareas the females remain only long enough to mate(Sivinski amd Petersson, 1997).

label.value: formation of assembly near vertebrate host

value.value: Males of a number of species of Aedes and Mansonia assemble around the warm-blooded hosts on which the females feed, and attempt to couple with virgin females that also respond to the host.

definition.value:
These males have a well developed Johnston's organ, and it is likely that in most of these species the females' wing tone is an important cue for the final orientation of males to a female.
We may note here the assembly of males at the feeding site of a non-blood-sucking mosquito. Females of the autogenous species Malaya leei hover over a procession of ants on a tree trunk and, from time to time, settle to obtain regutgitated fluid from an ant. Males often appeared behind the hovering females and mated with them , completing the act within few seconds.

label.value: formation of assembly at emergence site

value.value: In a few species, sexually mature males aggregate at the emergence sites, congregating on or near the water surface. Depending on species, they respond to pupae, to emerging females, to newly emerged females or to teneral females. In most of these species the male antennae are modified. Such males do not respond to the female wing-beat tone. In species in which respond to pupae, the male forelegs are modified. In all of these species, the males beome sexually competent only after inversion of their terminalia, which takes a period of hours, but females are sexually receptive at the time of emergence.

definition.value: Species that exhibit this kind of behaviour are, Opifex fuscus, Deinocerites cancer, Culiseta inornata, and the genuses Aedes and Psorophora.

The chemical stimuli are organic and inorganic constituents of host odour. Mosquitos respond to some of these kairomones at a distance from the host as they are carried by the wind, and they respond to some at very short range as they are carried in convection currents.

value.value: The insect's natural habitat can evoke a response because of the produced visual images.
Mosquitoes variably approach or avoid visible objects. The responses of mosquitoes to artificial objects have important implications for trap design, but their biological significance is uncertain.

Mosquitoes (night-flying) may alter their flight paths when confronted with barriers, even when the barriers contain apertures large enough for their passage. Observations showed associations between mosquito flight paths and conspicuous features of the landscape.

Mosquitoes species differ in flight capacity, but to speak of an individual species flight range is incorrect because the distances are greatly affected by weather conditions (i.e. wind) and ecological variables.

Feeding on nectar and other plant juices provides an immediate energy source and permits the formation of carbohydrate and lipid reserves.

label.value: formation of carbohydrate and lipid reserves

value.value: Feeding on sugar, and, for females, on blood, leads to accumulations of fat and glycogen.

definition.value: Experiments with females of Aedes sollicitans, Aedes taeniorhynchus and Aedes aegypti shoed that a hormonal mechanism determined wether ingested sugar was converted to glycogen or fat. Females of Aedes sollicitans that ingested a large bloodmeal after a period of starvation fully replenished their stores of glycogen and triacylglycerol.

label.value: release and conservation of energy from sugar

value.value: Three major processes are involved in the release of energy from sugars: (i) glycolysis, which ends in the production of pyruvate; (ii) oxidation in the tricarboxylic acid (TCA) cycle; and (iii) further oxidation in the respiratory chain (oxidative phosphorylation).

label.value: accumulation and use of the carbohydrate and lipid reserve

value.value: The carbohydrate and lipid reserves present in most mosquitoes at emergence are insufficient for more than a few days' life and, for all males and the females of many species, must be replenished by feeding on plant sugars. A portion of the digestion products from blood meals in converted to glycogen and lipids, the proportion varying with species and with size of female.

definition.value: It has been suggested that some anophelines use the first blood meal primarily for the synthesis of maternal reserves. Sufficient is known to indicate that in general the metabolic pathways of culicids conform with those of other insects.

value.value: The oogonia in the end chamber or germanium become differentiated into oocytes and nurse cells. As the oocytes move backwards they become surrounded by the follicle cells of somatic origin, which compose the hind part of the germarium, and each oocyte in its follicle forms an egg chamber of the vitellarium. As the oocyte grows the cells finally arrange themselves in a single layer.

During mosquito embryogenesis pole cells form after cleavage energids have entered the posterior periplasm with its polar granules. The pole mirgrate in to two groups and settled in the 6th abdominal segment, where they become surrounded by mesodermal sheaths and form the gonad rudiments. The pole cells are now called primordial germ cells. By the 4th larval instar the ovaries are already distinct and contain cell clusters within a matrix of smaller cells, the interstitial tissue. By the early pupal stage each ovary has reformed into a group of ovarioles. Later in the pupal stage each ovariole differentiate into a germarium amd a vitellarium compromising one, two or even three ovarian follicles.
Gravid females of Culex quinquefasciatus and Cx tarsalis oviposit preferentially on water where already egg rafts have been laid.

definition.value: Similar apical droplets have been described from a number of species of Culex, Culiseta, Uranotaenia that lay their eggs in rafts. In Culex, apical droplets are known from pipiens, quinquefasciatus, stigmatosoma, tarsalis and erythrothorax of subgenus Culex and from apicalis of subgenus Neoculex. In Culiseta they are known from annulata and incidens of subgenus Culiseta, and longiareolata of subgenus Allotheobaldia. In Uranotaenia they are known from anhydor of subgenus Pseudoficalbia. Chemical analysis revealed the oviposition aggregation pheromone of Culex quinquefasciatus to be the (-)-(5R,6S) stereoisomer of the fatty-acid lactone 6-acetoxy-5-hexadecanolide.

value.value: Histochemical studies combined with the use of radioactive tracers and electron microscopy have largely confirmed that there is active synthesis and emission of RNA from the nucleus, and thence from the nucleus of the oocyte to the cytoplasm. Some of the proteins of the egg are synthetized in the nurse cells and follicular cells.

definition.value: The four phases are: (1) prvitellogenic phase, (2) initiation phase, (3) trophic phase and (4) post-trophic phase.

value.value: The chorion is the part of the egg shell that is secreted before oviposition by the follicular epithelium, a maternal tissue.

Secretion occurs in two phases and results in formation of the two layers of the chorion, the endochorion and exochorion. Use of the terms 'vitelline membrane' or 'vitelline envelope' for the endochorion is inappropriate.

label.value: hardening and darkening of the chorion

value.value: At oviposition the eggs are soft and white but within an hour the chorion begins to darken and harden. Colour development is uniform over the entire surface of the egg, and after 4h the egg shell looks black and is relatively firm. Superficially at least this process resembles sclerotization.

The definition concerns the eggs of Aedes aegypti.
Untanned chorions separated from newly laid eggs were colourless, but when chorions were isolated after they had hardened and darkened naturally , the endochorion appeared brownish-grey and the exochorion colourless.

value.value: Flying in the absense of resource cues.

label.value: activation while settled on a support

value.value: Mosquitoes can be activated by host cues at any time. Unfed, resting females of some species will attack at any hour if disturbed in their shelters by intrusion of a host or stimulated by odour from a nearby host. Such opportunistic biting has been observed in nocturnal mosquitoes disturbed by day. The activation step is readily observed in the laboratory but has seldom been described from the field.
If the stimulus is sight of a moving host, the activated mosquito, may fly directly to the host.
If the stimulus is olfactory but there is no air movement, as can happen in the laboratory the response is kinetic, i.e an increase in flight speed or frequency of turning.

Known kairomones include carbon dioxide, octenol, lactic acid and water vapour. Carbon dioxide activates mosquitoes and is used in odour-mediated anemotaxis. Octenol and lactic acid act additively and possibly in some instances synergistically with carbon dioxide.
Aliphatic acids and other unidentified products of the skin surface serve as kairomones. Certain constituents or hydrolytic products of urine possibly also serve as kairomone.
Mosquitoes can detect heat transfer from vertebrate hosts over short distances, and the manner of heat transfer to which they respond is the subject of the section.

The role of vision in host finding may differ between day- and night- flying species. Mosquitoes respond to host movement. Night-flying mosquitoes that were beleived to be ranging flight would alter their heading to fly towards inanimate physical objects. value.value: Mosquitos have the ability to apprehend certain volatile host emanations in the air. Only if there is an air movement can they fly towards a distant odour source. If there is not an air movement the mosquitos are unable to orient themselves to the source of the volatiles.

The muscles of insects fall into two groups; the skeletal muscle forming bands across the articulations of the body wall, which serve to move one segment on another, and the visceral muscles which invest the internal organs.
The insect rests during walking on a supporting triangle, formed by the anterior and posterior limb on one side and the middle limb on the other, while it carries forward the other three legs.

The nervous arcs through which co-ordination is effected lie in the thoracic ganglia. The fore leg acts as a tractor; the middle leg serves for support, lifting the body on its own side and together with the hind leg raising the posterior part of the body; the hind leg acts as a propulsor and also turns the body in the horizontal plane. The three legs forming the tripod for a time being are not lifted simultaneously but in the order: i)fore-leg ii)opposite middle leg iii)hind-leg.

Only the paddles, powered by the abdominal muscles, function as propulsive organs. The rest of the body has no locomotory function other tham balancing forces of the paddle stroke.
Some larvae walk by means of their thoracic legs in the same manner as adult forms; but they are often aided by provisional modifications of the abdomen.

Larvae use their abdominal muscles to cause a lateral flexure of the abdomen. The massive abdominal muscles that provide the power for larval locomotion persist through the pupal and pharate-adult stages.
The movement of adult mosquitoes in the air currents. Defined as slowly falling at less than 45 degrees from the horizontal.

The lower Diptera (Tipulids) have long thin abdomens and long legs which probably ensure their stabilityduring flight. In higher forms (Muscids) their wings-beats create a resultant force which is equal to or greater than the weight of the insect.
